# Cline Rules — OpenFOAM Mixing Tank Project

## Environment
- Always activate venv before running any Python/shell command:
  `source venv/bin/activate` (Linux/Mac) or `venv\Scripts\activate` (Windows)
- Never run pip/python commands without venv active. Verify with `which python` first if unsure.

## Token efficiency
- No explanations unless asked. Output code/commands only.
- No restating the task before acting.
- No summaries after task completion — just confirm done in 1 line.
- Skip preamble like "I will now..." — just execute.
- Read only files directly relevant to current subtask, not entire repo.
- Don't re-read files already shown in context this session.

## OpenFOAM conventions
- Case structure fixed: 0/, constant/, system/. Never create dirs outside this.
- STL geometry lives only in constant/triSurface/.
- Follow this exact meshing order, never reorder:
  surfaceFeatureExtract -> blockMesh -> snappyHexMesh -overwrite -> 
  renumberMesh -overwrite -> createPatch -overwrite
- Do not auto-populate dictionary files with default/example content unless 
  explicitly instructed — empty scaffolding only until told otherwise.
- Match OpenFOAM.com/ESI syntax (v1906-v2606), not OpenFOAM Foundation syntax.

## Output style
- Plain text status updates, no markdown headers in chat responses.
- Flag errors immediately, don't attempt silent retries more than once.

# .clinerules

## Project
OpenFOAM v2406 case: two-phase (water/air) stirred-tank mixer, interFoam
solver, rotating impeller via AMI. Geometry: tank.STL, impeller.STL,
ami.STL in constant/triSurface/. Impeller top sits 10mm below tank top.

## Environment
- Host OS: Windows. OpenFOAM runs inside WSL2 Ubuntu, not natively on Windows.
- All OpenFOAM commands (blockMesh, snappyHexMesh, interFoam, etc.) must be run from the Ubuntu WSL terminal, never PowerShell/cmd.
- OpenFOAM install: openfoam2406-default via OpenFOAM.com apt repo.
- Environment must be sourced each session: source /usr/lib/openfoam/openfoam2406/etc/bashrc (this line should already be in ~/.bashrc — verify before assuming a fresh terminal has it).
- Verify utilities on PATH before running any mesh/solve step: blockMesh -help, checkMesh -help, snappyHexMesh -help must return usage text, not "command not found".
- Confirm active version with: echo $WM_PROJECT_VERSION (expect 2406).
- Windows case folder is reachable from WSL at /mnt/c/Users/JoshuaAlcobiaGomes/Desktop/OpenFoam Mixing Tank. For meshing performance, prefer copying the case into the Linux filesystem (e.g. ~/mixingTank) before running snappyHexMesh.
- ParaView runs on the Windows side; access WSL case files from Windows via \\wsl$\Ubuntu\home\... if the case was copied into the Linux filesystem.

## Mesh Execution Order (strict, do not reorder or skip)
1. surfaceFeatureExtract
2. blockMesh
3. snappyHexMesh -overwrite
4. renumberMesh -overwrite
5. createPatch -overwrite
6. checkMesh
7. setFields
8. interFoam

Stop immediately on any non-zero exit code or FATAL ERROR. Report the exact error text before proceeding to the next command. Do not re-run earlier steps (e.g. surfaceFeatureExtract, blockMesh) unless STL geometry or blockMeshDict actually changed.

## Dictionary File Rules
- Do not edit any of the 18 case dictionary files unless explicitly instructed — they have been verified correct.
- dynamicMeshDict cellZone name (rotatingZone) must match exactly what is defined in snappyHexMeshDict's ami refinementSurface (cellZone + faceZone).
- createPatchDict splits the rotatingZone faceZone into ami1/ami2, both type cyclicAMI, each other's neighbourPatch.

## Coarse Mesh Constraint (current phase)
- Target background cell size: ~1cm, set via blockMeshDict divisions based on tank.STL bounding box.
- Keep all snappyHexMeshDict refinementSurfaces at level (0 0) — no extra refinement layered on top of the 1cm base grid.
- Skip addLayers at this stage.
- Goal is confirming AMI + rotatingMotion + VoF setup runs without divergence, not accuracy.

## ParaView / Results
- Case must be opened via an empty placeholder file with .foam extension (e.g. paraview.foam) at case root, next to 0/, constant/, system/.
- If ParaView reports "contains no meshes," check in this order: constant/polyMesh populated (points, faces, owner, neighbour, boundary non-empty) → parallel decomposition not reconstructed (run reconstructParMesh -constant if processor* folders exist) → checkMesh output for zero cells or fatal errors → OpenFOAM actually installed and on PATH.
- Never regenerate the .foam placeholder as a first troubleshooting step — confirm the mesh itself is valid first.

## Efficiency Rules
- Run checkMesh once, immediately after createPatch -overwrite, not after every sub-step.
- Default to serial execution for this coarse mesh; only parallelize (decomposePar + snappyHexMesh -parallel + reconstructParMesh) if cell count exceeds ~500k.
- Use short endTime (a few impeller revolutions) for functionality checks, not full production duration.
- Use adjustableRunTime with maxCo 5 rather than small fixed deltaT.
- Defer turbulence tuning and surface-layer addition until the coarse mesh confirms stability.
- On early divergence, check AMI patch-weight warnings in the log before re-meshing — bad AMI overlap is the cheapest failure mode to diagnose.